#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:265(title)
msgid "Disappearing Images"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:266(para)
msgid "At the end of 2012, Cybera (a nonprofit with a mandate to oversee the development of cyberinfrastructure in Alberta, Canada) deployed an updated OpenStack cloud for their <link title=\"DAIR project\" href=\"http://www.canarie.ca/en/dair-program/about\">DAIR project</link> (http://www.canarie.ca/en/dair-program/about). A few days into production, a compute node locks up. Upon rebooting the node, I checked to see what instances were hosted on that node so I could boot them on behalf of the customer. Luckily, only one instance."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:277(para)
msgid "The <code>nova reboot</code> command wasn't working, so I used <code>virsh</code>, but it immediately came back with an error saying it was unable to find the backing disk. In this case, the backing disk is the Glance image that is copied to <code>/var/lib/nova/instances/_base</code> when the image is used for the first time. Why couldn't it find it? I checked the directory and sure enough it was gone."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:286(para)
msgid "I reviewed the <code>nova</code> database and saw the instance's entry in the <code>nova.instances</code> table. The image that the instance was using matched what virsh was reporting, so no inconsistency there."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:290(para)
msgid "I checked Glance and noticed that this image was a snapshot that the user created. At least that was good news — this user would have been the only user affected."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:294(para)
msgid "Finally, I checked StackTach and reviewed the user's events. They had created and deleted several snapshots — most likely experimenting. Although the timestamps didn't match up, my conclusion was that they launched their instance and then deleted the snapshot and it was somehow removed from <code>/var/lib/nova/instances/_base</code>. None of that made sense, but it was the best I could come up with."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:303(para)
msgid "It turns out the reason that this compute node locked up was a hardware issue. We removed it from the DAIR cloud and called Dell to have it serviced. Dell arrived and began working. Somehow or another (or a fat finger), a different compute node was bumped and rebooted. Great."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:309(para)
msgid "When this node fully booted, I ran through the same scenario of seeing what instances were running so I could turn them back on. There were a total of four. Three booted and one gave an error. It was the same error as before: unable to find the backing disk. Seriously, what?"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:315(para)
msgid "Again, it turns out that the image was a snapshot. The three other instances that successfully started were standard cloud images. Was it a problem with snapshots? That didn't make sense."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:319(para)
msgid "A note about DAIR's architecture: <code>/var/lib/nova/instances</code> is a shared NFS mount. This means that all compute nodes have access to it, which includes the <code>_base</code> directory. Another centralized area is <code>/var/log/rsyslog</code> on the cloud controller. This directory collects all OpenStack logs from all compute nodes. I wondered if there were any entries for the file that <code>virsh</code> is reporting:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:329(code)
msgid "dair-ua-c03/nova.log:Dec 19 12:10:59 dair-ua-c03 2012-12-19 12:10:59 INFO nova.virt.libvirt.imagecache [-] Removing base file: /var/lib/nova/instances/_base/7b4783508212f5d242cbf9ff56fb8d33b4ce6166_10"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:334(para)
msgid "Ah-hah! So OpenStack was deleting it. But why?"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:335(para)
msgid "A feature was introduced in Essex to periodically check and see if there were any _base files not in use. If there were, Nova would delete them. This idea sounds innocent enough and has some good qualities to it. But how did this feature end up turned on? It was disabled by default in Essex. As it should be. It was <link href=\"https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1029674\">decided to be turned on in Folsom</link> (https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1029674). I cannot emphasize enough that:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:346(emphasis)
msgid "Actions which delete things should not be enabled by default."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:349(para)
msgid "Disk space is cheap these days. Data recovery is not."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:351(para)
msgid "Secondly, DAIR's shared <code>/var/lib/nova/instances</code> directory contributed to the problem. Since all compute nodes have access to this directory, all compute nodes periodically review the _base directory. If there is only one instance using an image, and the node that the instance is on is down for a few minutes, it won't be able to mark the image as still in use. Therefore, the image seems like it's not in use and is deleted. When the compute node comes back online, the instance hosted on that node is unable to start."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:364(title)
msgid "The Valentine's Day Compute Node Massacre"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:365(para)
msgid "Although the title of this story is much more dramatic than the actual event, I don't think, or hope, that I'll have the opportunity to use \"Valentine's Day Massacre\" again in a title."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:369(para)
msgid "This past Valentine's Day, I received an alert that a compute node was no longer available in the cloud — meaning,"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:373(para)
msgid "showed this particular node with a status of <code>XXX</code>."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:375(para)
msgid "I logged into the cloud controller and was able to both ping and SSH into the problematic compute node which seemed very odd. Usually if I receive this type of alert, the compute node has totally locked up and would be inaccessible."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:380(para)
msgid "After a few minutes of troubleshooting, I saw the following details:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:384(para)
msgid "A user recently tried launching a CentOS instance on that node"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:388(para)
msgid "This user was the only user on the node (new node)"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:392(para)
msgid "The load shot up to 8 right before I received the alert"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:396(para)
msgid "The bonded 10gb network device (bond0) was in a DOWN state"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:400(para)
msgid "The 1gb NIC was still alive and active"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:403(para)
msgid "I looked at the status of both NICs in the bonded pair and saw that neither was able to communicate with the switch port. Seeing as how each NIC in the bond is connected to a separate switch, I thought that the chance of a switch port dying on each switch at the same time was quite improbable. I concluded that the 10gb dual port NIC had died and needed replaced. I created a ticket for the hardware support department at the data center where the node was hosted. I felt lucky that this was a new node and no one else was hosted on it yet."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:413(para)
msgid "An hour later I received the same alert, but for another compute node. Crap. OK, now there's definitely a problem going on. Just like the original node, I was able to log in by SSH. The bond0 NIC was DOWN but the 1gb NIC was active."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:418(para)
msgid "And the best part: the same user had just tried creating a CentOS instance. Wat?"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:420(para)
msgid "I was totally confused at this point, so I texted our network admin to see if he was available to help. He logged in to both switches and immediately saw the problem: the switches detected spanning tree packets coming from the two compute nodes and immediately shut the ports down to prevent spanning tree loops:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:432(para)
msgid "He re-enabled the switch ports and the two compute nodes immediately came back to life."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:434(para)
msgid "Unfortunately, this story has an open ending... we're still looking into why the CentOS image was sending out spanning tree packets. Further, we're researching a proper way on how to mitigate this from happening. It's a bigger issue than one might think. While it's extremely important for switches to prevent spanning tree loops, it's very problematic to have an entire compute node be cut from the network when this happens. If a compute node is hosting 100 instances and one of them sends a spanning tree packet, that instance has effectively DDOS'd the other 99 instances."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:445(para)
msgid "This is an ongoing and hot topic in networking circles — especially with the raise of virtualization and virtual switches."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:450(title)
msgid "Down the Rabbit Hole"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:451(para)
msgid "Users being able to retrieve console logs from running instances is a boon for support — many times they can figure out what's going on inside their instance and fix what's going on without bothering you. Unfortunately, sometimes overzealous logging of failures can cause problems of its own."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:457(para)
msgid "A report came in: VMs were launching slowly, or not at all. Cue the standard checks — nothing on the nagios, but there was a spike in network towards the current master of our RabbitMQ cluster. Investigation started, but soon the other parts of the queue cluster were leaking memory like a sieve. Then the alert came in — the master rabbit server went down. Connections failed over to the slave."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:464(para)
msgid "At that time, our control services were hosted by another team and we didn't have much debugging information to determine what was going on with the master, and couldn't reboot it. That team noted that it failed without alert, but managed to reboot it. After an hour, the cluster had returned to its normal state and we went home for the day."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:471(para)
msgid "Continuing the diagnosis the next morning was kick started by another identical failure. We quickly got the message queue running again, and tried to work out why Rabbit was suffering from so much network traffic. Enabling debug logging on nova-api quickly brought understanding. A <code>tail -f /var/log/nova/nova-api.log</code> was scrolling by faster than we'd ever seen before. CTRL+C on that and we could plainly see the contents of a system log spewing failures over and over again - a system log from one of our users' instances."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:482(para)
msgid "After finding the instance ID we headed over to <code>/var/lib/nova/instances</code> to find the <code>console.log</code>:"
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:489(para)
msgid "Sure enough, the user had been periodically refreshing the console log page on the dashboard and the 5G file was traversing the rabbit cluster to get to the dashboard."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:493(para)
msgid "We called them and asked them to stop for a while, and they were happy to abandon the horribly broken VM. After that, we started monitoring the size of console logs."
msgstr ""

#: ./doc/src/docbkx/openstack-ops/src/app_crypt.xml:497(para)
msgid "To this day, <link href=\"https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/832507\">the issue</link> (https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/832507) doesn't have a permanent resolution, but we look forward to the discussion at the next summit."
msgstr ""

